Life expectancy improvement for multiple cure distributions.

Naik S(1), Adamic P(1).

Author information:
(1)Laurentian University, Sudbury, Canada.

In many circumstances, the increase in life expectancy when certain causes of 
death are eliminated is sought. These calculations are typically based on the 
assumption that the causes in question are simply omitted, which is equivalent 
to the causes being taken out of consideration, from the outset, with certainty. 
In this paper, we propose models whereby probability distributions for the cures 
of specific causes of death over time can be incorporated so as to more 
accurately predict the increase in life expectancy that would ensue. The 
theoretical results are applied to a real data set involving Diabetes and 
HIV-related deaths from Denver, Colorado, United States of America, between the 
years 1990 and 2015 inclusive.

